[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] When you create a new load test, one of the first steps is to define the HTTP requests that you would like to test.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] The http module handles all kinds of HTTP requests and methods.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] By default, k6 automatically follows a set number of redirects before stopping and returning the last response.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] k6 automatically applies tags to your HTTP requests.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] You can use these tags to filter your results and organize your analysis.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] The following snippet shows a JSON example of how a test-result data point is logged.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] In this example, the metric is the duration of an HTTP request.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] By default, tags have a `name` field that holds the value of the request URL.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] If your test has dynamic URL paths, you might not want this behavior, which could bring a large number of unique URLs into the metrics stream.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] Note how these two objects have the same `name`, despite having different URLs.
[src:k6-load-testing/http-requests] If you filter the results for the tag `name: PostsItemURL`, the results include all data points from all 100 URLs.
[src:k6-load-testing/k6-software] K6 was initially released by LoadImpact in 2017.
[src:k6-load-testing/k6-software] LoadImpact was later rebranded into k6 in 2020.
[src:k6-load-testing/k6-software] K6 was then acquired by Grafana Labs in 2021.
[src:k6-load-testing/k6-software] It has since become a popular tool for performance testing in the developer community.
[src:k6-load-testing/k6-software] The below script executes a GET request on the Wikipedia homepage, checks whether the HTTP status code is 200 and if we are using the HTTP/2 protocol.
[src:k6-load-testing/k6-software] The above test case can be run with the command `$ k6 run http_2.js` where `http_2.js` is the filename in which the test case is saved in.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] Many types of machinery, engines, structures, and motors are load tested.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] The load may be at a designated safe working load (SWL), full load, or at an aggravated level of load.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] The governing contract, technical specification or test method contains the details of conducting the test.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] The purpose of a mechanical load test is to verify that all the component parts of a structure including materials, base-fixings are fit for task and loading it is designed for.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] The *Supply of Machinery (Safety) Regulation 1992 UK* state that load testing is undertaken before the equipment is put into service for the first time.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] Performance testing applies a safe working load (SWL), or other specified load, for a designated time in a governing test method, specification, or contract.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] Under the *Lifting Operations and Lifting Equipment Regulations 1998 UK* load testing after the initial test is required if a major component is replaced, if the item is moved from one location to another or as dictated by the competent person.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] The term *load testing* or stress testing is used in different ways in the professional software testing community.
[src:k6-load-testing/load-testing] *Load testing* generally refers to the practice of modeling the expected usage of a software program by simulating multiple users accessing the program concurrently.
[src:k6-load-testing/page] Grafana k6 is an open-source, developer-friendly, and extensible performance testing tool that helps you catch performance issues early and proactively improve reliability.
[src:k6-load-testing/page] Using k6, you can test the reliability and performance of your application and infrastructure.
[src:k6-load-testing/page] k6 helps engineering teams prevent errors and SLO breaches, enabling them to build resilient and high-performing applications that scale.
[src:k6-load-testing/page] Watch the video below to learn more about k6 and why it could be the missing puzzle in your Grafana stack.
